Well, there's the segue.

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:02.210
So we want, we don't
want the green,

00:05:02.210 --> 00:05:05.090
but we more or less
expect the green, right?

00:05:05.090 --> 00:05:07.150
If you get it,
you pass the exam.

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:08.780
If you pass the
exam, you get it.

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:11.360
That's that, and we like
to have lots of people

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:13.220
have that happen too.

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.627
And then we also
acknowledge that somebody

00:05:15.627 --> 00:05:17.210
isn't going to get
it, and they're not

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:18.920
and they're not going
to pass the exam.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:24.080
And that kind of maybe makes us
sad, but it's not surprising.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:25.850
And then anybody
can kind of have

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:28.680
a bad day or kind of a fluke.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:30.830
So sometimes, sure,
somebody will fail the exam,

00:05:30.830 --> 00:05:33.590
and actually really
understand the material.

00:05:33.590 --> 00:05:35.780
Generally speaking,
that doesn't happen,

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:38.030
and then there's
often a reason for it.

00:05:38.030 --> 00:05:40.220
But it's that red
circle that Rachel

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:47.354
mentioned that is troublesome,
at the least, troublesome.

00:05:47.354 --> 00:05:48.395
So why might that happen?

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:56.170
Why so many red circles?

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:56.670
Yeah, Dave.

00:05:56.670 --> 00:05:59.340
AUDIENCE: Because the test was
set up for basic memorization,

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:01.416
