00:06:28.681 --> 00:06:31.394
They often told us
too much of what

00:06:31.394 --> 00:06:32.560
was going to be on the exam.

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:34.350
And so then you
kind of just knew

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:36.952
what the test was going to
be if you could well on it

00:06:36.952 --> 00:06:38.266
if you [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:38.266 --> 00:06:39.550
JANET RANKIN: OK.

00:06:39.550 --> 00:06:40.660
That's interesting.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:41.484
Yes, Gordon.

00:06:41.484 --> 00:06:46.278
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it's
possible that [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:46.278 --> 00:06:50.742
tests [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:50.742 --> 00:06:54.230
When it comes to true life
situations and something

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.730
that [INAUDIBLE]
knowledge that was

00:06:56.730 --> 00:07:00.674
gained from that material,
then [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:03.765 --> 00:07:04.860
JANET RANKIN: OK.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:13.020
So Gordon is sort of kind of
flirting with this idea of you

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:15.374
as the instructor, this
real life knowledge,

00:07:15.374 --> 00:07:16.290
this is what it means.

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:19.500
They have to have this practical
working knowledge for us

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:24.340
as the instructors to
say they got it, right?

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:26.650
But the exam isn't measuring it.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:29.800
And that's exactly what, that's
what Dave was saying as well.

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:32.920
This idea that the exam
is measuring one thing,

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:36.610
but it's not really measuring
whether they got it.

00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:38.380
When we go home
and think what does

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:40.900
it mean to be a good
material scientist,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:42.659
or what does it mean
to be a good chemist,

00:07:42.659 --> 00:07:44.200
we don't think, oh,
it means that you

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:46.520
can define what a
mitochondria is,

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:49.790
or you can balance
a simple equation.

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:57.450
And yet, we put
that on the exam.

00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:59.430
It's also a bit of
the idea that students

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:00.900
are good at taking tests.

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.000
They're good at gaming systems.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.180
They're good at listening to
TAs or TAs may have not given

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.860
out appropriate information.

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:09.750
So it comes from both sides.

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:13.620
It comes from the students and
it comes from the professors.

00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:16.920
But you have control over this.

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:20.430
You shouldn't be writing
an exam that people

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:24.090
can get a good grade on,
but then when you go home

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:26.400
and say, oh, they got a
good grade on this test,

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:28.340
but they didn't get it.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:32.600
You need to define what it
means to get it in your field,

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:37.789
to get this subject, whatever
it is that the test is about.

00:08:37.789 --> 00:08:42.890
And then you need to write
a test that measures that.

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:45.920
And too many times
we don't do it.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.020
We're kind of rushed,
or we don't really know.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:49.936
We haven't really thought
about how to measure

00:08:49.936 --> 00:08:52.980
whether somebody gets it.

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:56.540
So the first step in all
this is to define what it

00:08:56.540 --> 00:09:00.520
is that means that they got it.

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:03.680
And that's the first step,
and that's the hardest step.

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:06.590
But once that's done,
the rest is easier,

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:11.042
and it will save you from this.

00:09:11.042 --> 00:09:12.521
OK?

00:09:12.521 --> 00:09:15.490
OK.

