JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.780
It's very detailed
at a certain level,

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:52.420
but it's still really
hard to understand, right?

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:53.800
Any other ideas?

00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:54.300
Yes.

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.300
AUDIENCE: I think
it's interesting.

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:58.300
There's a lot of value
judgements in it.

00:13:58.300 --> 00:13:59.712
Like, it's really easy.

00:13:59.712 --> 00:14:02.450
And one can never tell
with comments like that.

00:14:02.450 --> 00:14:05.052
Because I'm trained to figure
out what they're saying,

00:14:05.052 --> 00:14:07.522
it's actually just
frustrating me more,

00:14:07.522 --> 00:14:10.230
because I don't know what
they're talking about.

00:14:10.230 --> 00:14:12.271
And it's really easy--

00:14:12.271 --> 00:14:13.270
JANET RANKIN: All right.

00:14:13.270 --> 00:14:15.729
So that's a great point.

00:14:15.729 --> 00:14:17.770
So we're talking about
writing learning outcomes,

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:19.660
about organizing the
course around writing

00:14:19.660 --> 00:14:20.570
learning outcomes.

00:14:20.570 --> 00:14:22.450
If you're using
phrases, or you're

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:24.820
using language
that's just, there's

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:28.960
just like throwaway words
in there or value judgments,

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:33.700
it's not doing your
students any good, right?

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:37.690
And also, that if you have
this beautiful course that's

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:41.320
beautifully organized even,
wonderfully organized,

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:44.230
but if you don't tell
them what it is you're

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:45.910
trying to do with it all--

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:47.680
what it is they're
going to be able to do

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:52.410
with it all, whatever it
is you expect them to do--

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:55.600
they're not going to
be able to follow you.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:58.300
So imagine a procedure
as fairly straightforward

00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:00.640
as doing the laundry.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.650
Now imagine, OK,
you're going to be

00:15:02.650 --> 00:15:05.950
able to select the right,
the appropriate method

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:14.440
to integrate equations,
so methods of integration,

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:20.770
by separation, by card or
substitution or whatever.

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:22.990
So if you don't
tell them what it

00:15:22.990 --> 00:15:24.580
is you're expecting
them to do, even

00:15:24.580 --> 00:15:26.746
if you're very good at
explaining what it is they're

00:15:26.746 --> 00:15:30.740
going to do, they won't get it.

00:15:30.740 --> 00:15:34.570
So this is my sell for why when
you write a learning outcome,

00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:36.940
you have to write a learning
outcome that's clear

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:40.090
and that's understandable to
the students, that doesn't have

00:15:40.090 --> 00:15:42.130
a lot of extra words
and that tells them

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:44.220
exactly what they're
supposed to do.

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:54.520
So I have some learning
outcomes for today

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:56.680
and I hope that they're clear.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:15:59.110
You'll be able to
describe the components

00:15:59.110 --> 00:16:03.640
of the constructive alignment
and backward design processes.

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:05.860
And those, constructive
alignment anyway,

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:08.290
was in the pre-class reading.

00:16:08.290 --> 00:16:10.810
You'll be able to classify
the content of a course

00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:12.010
that you might teach.

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:17.170
So what do I expect students
to do with this content,

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:18.770
to be able to do
with this content?

00:16:18.770 --> 00:16:22.600
You'll be able to create
measurable, specific, and

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:26.530
realistic learning outcomes
for a class you will teach,

00:16:26.530 --> 00:16:30.310
and you'll be able to state
the components of a syllabus.

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:33.280
So I feel that those are
pretty understandable.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:39.500
You may disagree with me,
or maybe you want to wait.

00:16:43.450 --> 00:16:46.720
So constructive alignment, it
was in the pre-class reading,

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:48.430
right?

00:16:48.430 --> 00:16:51.930
Anybody want to just give
a brief summary of it?

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:58.210
I mean it's kind of up
here, but in your own--

00:16:58.210 --> 00:17:00.020
AUDIENCE: I think
constructive alignment

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:09.468
is about aligning assessment,
method of assessment,

00:17:09.468 --> 00:17:12.280
with course content.

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:15.230
[INAUDIBLE] assess
[INAUDIBLE] type of assessment

00:17:15.230 --> 00:17:18.670
so that what the teacher
has in mind, the course

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:21.973
content or the content
I want them to get,

00:17:21.973 --> 00:17:24.329
to test it with the
assessment process.

00:17:24.329 --> 00:17:27.209
Then we would also
do the assessment,

00:17:27.209 --> 00:17:32.497
and then come up with
the intended outcome.

00:17:32.497 --> 00:17:33.330
JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:34.913
They'll achieve the
learning outcomes.

00:17:34.913 --> 00:17:36.870
And if you do this
right, you get rid

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:40.380
of that red circle
on that graph.

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:44.280
You get rid of students who
did well on the assessment

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:46.680
but don't really
know what's going on,

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:49.320
because you have
aligned the assessment

00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:53.310
with what it was you wanted
them to know or be able to do.

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:56.100
So that's important.

00:17:56.100 --> 00:17:59.130
I just think this is a
very, very compelling image

00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:03.360
to keep in your head, that these
three things have to be linked.

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:05.964
And as I said before,
this, you will

00:18:05.964 --> 00:18:08.130
see that the top part,
writing the learning outcomes

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:09.870
is the tricky part,
it's the hard part.

00:18:09.870 --> 00:18:13.080
It's the part that requires
a lot of thinking and work.

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:15.010
When you get a good
learning outcome,

00:18:15.010 --> 00:18:21.090
the other two things almost
take care of themselves.

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:22.790
OK?

00:18:22.790 --> 00:18:24.290
Did anybody have
any, does anybody

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:26.379
have any questions
about something

00:18:26.379 --> 00:18:28.670
from the reading associated
with constructive alignment

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:33.689
or some other idea
from the reading?

00:18:33.689 --> 00:18:34.188
Yes, Gordon.

00:18:34.188 --> 00:18:37.860
AUDIENCE: I just wanted
to make a contribution.

00:18:37.860 --> 00:18:42.344
I think that this constructive
alignment is one of the things

00:18:42.344 --> 00:18:46.005
that the intended
outcome should measure.

00:18:46.005 --> 00:19:03.262
So I think maybe that's
confusing [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:03.262 --> 00:19:06.496
and also how we can test
and be sure and confident.

00:19:06.496 --> 00:19:07.650
JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:19:07.650 --> 00:19:08.580
Right.

00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:12.620
I think the measurability part
for scientists and engineers

00:19:12.620 --> 00:19:15.390
is kind of intuitive.

00:19:15.390 --> 00:19:18.330
Like why would you say
something if you couldn't

00:19:18.330 --> 00:19:21.470
tell whether or not
it was true, or not

00:19:21.470 --> 00:19:24.060
from a scientific point of view.

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:27.380
What's the point
of saying, making

00:19:27.380 --> 00:19:28.930
a proclamation
about what somebody

00:19:28.930 --> 00:19:31.860
should be able to do if you
can't measure it in the end?

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:34.764
So it's comforting
to say, OK, I'm

00:19:34.764 --> 00:19:36.930
going to make learning
outcomes that are measurable.

00:19:36.930 --> 00:19:40.050
But it also can be
a bit challenging.

00:19:40.050 --> 00:19:41.010
But we'll do that.

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:44.110
We're going to do that today.

00:19:44.110 --> 00:19:45.130
Some other comment?

00:19:45.130 --> 00:19:45.630
Nina.

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:49.130
AUDIENCE: I guess as
far as [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:49.130 --> 00:19:51.078
Do people write
learning outcomes that

00:19:51.078 --> 00:19:54.850
have no constructive
alignment process,

00:19:54.850 --> 00:19:57.402
like choosing to write
learning outcomes,

00:19:57.402 --> 00:20:01.080
are you going
through the prcoess?

00:20:01.080 --> 00:20:03.732
It seems decoupled a
little bit in the reading,

00:20:03.732 --> 00:20:06.504
but it seems like you can't
have one without the other.

00:20:06.504 --> 00:20:09.424
JANET RANKIN: You
owe it to yourself--

00:20:09.424 --> 00:20:11.590
and I don't know what people
do, and I guarantee you

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:13.540
people write learning outcomes
without thinking about

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:15.415
whether they can assess
them or measure them,

00:20:15.415 --> 00:20:19.070
I guarantee that
happens in real life--

00:20:19.070 --> 00:20:22.500
you owe it to yourself to
try very hard not to do that.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:23.170
OK?

00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:27.070
And I think the important
thing to do is, often we say,

00:20:27.070 --> 00:20:29.260
oh, my god, this is
the best assignment.

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:31.300
This is the greatest question.

00:20:31.300 --> 00:20:33.400
It's this project, and
they're going to do this,

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:34.649
and they're going to whatever.

00:20:34.649 --> 00:20:36.970
They're going to
build a race car.

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:39.550
And if you sit down
and say, well, what

00:20:39.550 --> 00:20:41.970
do I want them to
get out of that?

00:20:41.970 --> 00:20:44.850
If you can't articulate it
in a way that's consistent

00:20:44.850 --> 00:20:46.920
with your class,
consistent with the course

00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:49.350
as it sits in this
series of their courses,

00:20:49.350 --> 00:20:51.750
or as it sits in
the institution,

00:20:51.750 --> 00:20:55.620
then you either need to
rethink the assignment,

00:20:55.620 --> 00:20:59.340
rethink the project, or
think a lot harder about what

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:03.740
learning outcomes that
activity advances.

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:06.840
That's a very good point.

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:08.640
It's really kind of iterative.

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:11.970
And I think it might be easier
to see with this diagram.

00:21:11.970 --> 00:21:15.660
This is another-- so John
Biggs is from the UK.

00:21:15.660 --> 00:21:19.320
And so there's sort of
the UK camp of people

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:21.030
and they like John Biggs.

00:21:21.030 --> 00:21:23.070
And then there's
Wiggins and McTighe.

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:26.550
Grant Wiggins and Jay
McTighe are from the US.

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:29.910
They wrote primarily for
the K through 12 audience,

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:32.460
but it's completely applicable.

00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:35.310
And they're from the US, so they
have kind of a US following.

00:21:35.310 --> 00:21:38.620
It's just how it works.

00:21:38.620 --> 00:21:40.810
It's essentially the same thing.

00:21:40.810 --> 00:21:44.520
It's identify the results, so
the intended learning outcomes.

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:47.070
Figure out how you're
going to get them there.

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:51.100
So the black is Wiggins and
McTighe and the red is Biggs.

00:21:51.100 --> 00:21:53.220
So plan the learning
experiences that

00:21:53.220 --> 00:21:55.410
are going to support them,
achieving the learning

00:21:55.410 --> 00:21:59.220
outcomes, and really help you
measure whether they got them

00:21:59.220 --> 00:22:00.310
or not.

00:22:00.310 --> 00:22:02.672
And then determine
what evidence will

00:22:02.672 --> 00:22:05.130
be that acceptable evidence
that they achieved the learning

00:22:05.130 --> 00:22:07.320
outcomes and what
are the assessments.

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:12.750
So real often we do have
this project that we want.

00:22:12.750 --> 00:22:14.130
Oh, this is a great problem.

00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:17.490
Often in thermo-- I taught a lot
of thermo-- there's like, oh,

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:21.150
they're going to do this
double loop, double reactor

00:22:21.150 --> 00:22:25.184
cycle with the refrigerant
and a heating cycle.

00:22:25.184 --> 00:22:26.850
And it's going to be
coupled and they're

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:29.870
going to use the output from
one for the input in the other

00:22:29.870 --> 00:22:31.350
and all this crazy stuff.

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:34.680
Like, this is a
great assignment.

00:22:34.680 --> 00:22:36.990
And you kind of, I know
this is a great assignment.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:40.290
If I can't back up
from this assignment--

00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:42.330
whether or not I put
it here or here--

00:22:42.330 --> 00:22:46.490
if I can't back up and say
after a successful completion

00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:50.730
of this assignment, you
will be able to describe

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:55.480
the components of
the Brayton cycle,

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:59.730
you will be able to define
the increase in entropy

00:22:59.730 --> 00:23:05.250
for a system with x boundaries,
If I can't articulate

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:08.550
those things, then I need to
either change the assignment,

00:23:08.550 --> 00:23:11.430
or, well, then I need to
change the assignment.

00:23:11.430 --> 00:23:12.180
OK?

00:23:12.180 --> 00:23:14.640
But you can start
with the activity,

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:16.140
and then back up
and say, well, what

00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:18.960
learning outcomes does
that support, and then,

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:19.890
am I OK with that?

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:23.140
Is that relevant to this class?

00:23:23.140 --> 00:23:26.370
So it's often a very iterative,
the arrows kind of go this way,

00:23:26.370 --> 00:23:28.038
but it's often iterative.

00:23:31.320 --> 00:23:37.800
So I had asked that you come
to class with some topics

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:39.570
from a class you're
likely to teach.

00:23:39.570 --> 00:23:41.340
That was on the assignment page.

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:45.300
If not, start thinking now.

00:23:45.300 --> 00:23:47.970
And so you want to have,
for most classes, most

00:23:47.970 --> 00:23:50.550
undergraduate classes,
there's a bunch of topics.

00:23:50.550 --> 00:23:53.910
You might have 10
topics, 20 topics.

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:57.796
And I don't care right now
about the scale of the topics,

00:23:57.796 --> 00:23:58.920
whether they're really big.

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:01.140
You probably don't want
to go with like first law,

00:24:01.140 --> 00:24:03.000
second law.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:07.130
That's probably a
little bit too big,

00:24:07.130 --> 00:24:12.360
but on the order
of 5 to 15 topics.

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:14.130
Jot down the topics.

00:24:14.130 --> 00:24:16.710
And then I have a chart here.

00:24:16.710 --> 00:24:21.450
So the chart has two
sides, and the columns

00:24:21.450 --> 00:24:23.700
are Bloom's Taxonomy,
which you don't

00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:25.770
have to worry about
that specifically,

00:24:25.770 --> 00:24:29.800
but you can look at the words
that are associated with it.

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:34.170
And then the second column
is what students should

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:36.960
be able to do with each topic.

00:24:36.960 --> 00:24:45.660
So let's say my topic is
first law for closed systems.

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:48.480
So I might think
about, OK, do I want

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:51.150
them to be able to
define, to just state

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:53.685
the first law for
closed systems?

00:24:53.685 --> 00:24:56.550
Do I want them to be able to
use the first law for closed

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:59.520
systems in order to solve
certain kinds of equations?

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:03.270
Do I want them to be able
to derive the first law?

00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:06.510
Do I want them to be
able, whatever it is.

00:25:06.510 --> 00:25:10.110
So you're going to look at
the columns, the categories

00:25:10.110 --> 00:25:12.657
on the left side,
and you're going

00:25:12.657 --> 00:25:13.740
to think about your topic.

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:16.830
And you're just going to decide
which box in the middle column

00:25:16.830 --> 00:25:18.802
to put the topics into.

00:25:18.802 --> 00:25:20.760
You don't have to worry
about writing anything.

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:26.430
You're just going to distribute
the topics to the level of,

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:29.534
it's really cognitive
processes that are associated

00:25:29.534 --> 00:25:30.700
with the things on the left.

00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:36.990
Remember, understand, apply,
analyze, evaluate, and create.

00:25:36.990 --> 00:25:39.460
So we'll take
about five minutes.

00:25:39.460 --> 00:25:41.230
And you just do
that by yourself.

00:25:41.230 --> 00:25:43.170
And just fill in
that middle column

00:25:43.170 --> 00:25:49.050
of the table with the
topics from your course.

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:50.890
Do you want more
explanation, Rachel?

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:59.240
It's starting to make
you think about this part

00:25:59.240 --> 00:26:05.020
of the beginning circle.

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:07.440
But you don't want to
write any sentences yet.

00:26:07.440 --> 00:26:10.460
But it's starting to help
you think about what are they

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:13.830
going to do with these topics.

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:15.130
What do I want them to do?

00:26:15.130 --> 00:26:20.350
Is it remember, or is it create
something using these things?

00:26:20.350 --> 00:26:21.290
Where is it?

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:22.970
Those are two ends
of the spectrum.

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:27.110
And in your chart, the
things that at the top

00:26:27.110 --> 00:26:28.940
are the more remember, right?

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:33.260
It's more about kind of
a recall information.

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:35.360
And then the things in
the back of the chart

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:40.160
tend to be more higher
order cognitive processes,

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:43.040
like synthesize, apply, create.

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:50.609
Yes.

00:26:50.609 --> 00:26:54.281
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:54.281 --> 00:26:57.050
JANET RANKIN: So don't worry
about the third column.

00:26:57.050 --> 00:26:58.940
Don't worry about
the last column yet.

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:00.326
We're going to do that later.

00:27:00.326 --> 00:27:01.700
So all you have
to do is just say

00:27:01.700 --> 00:27:05.410
where each topic falls loosely.

00:27:05.410 --> 00:27:05.910
OK.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.302
Does everybody have a chart?

00:27:08.302 --> 00:27:08.802
OK.

00:27:08.802 --> 00:27:10.730
AUDIENCE: Do you
want us to write

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:12.284
as many topics as possible?

00:27:12.284 --> 00:27:13.700
JANET RANKIN: Write
as many topics

00:27:13.700 --> 00:27:17.990
as possible, but distribute
them through the chart.

00:27:17.990 --> 00:27:19.460
Right?

00:27:19.460 --> 00:27:22.352
Not everything is going
to be remember, right?

00:27:22.352 --> 00:27:24.810
So some things will be remember,
some things will be apply,

00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:27.841
some things will be analyze,
some things will be create.

00:27:27.841 --> 00:27:28.340
OK?

00:27:31.950 --> 00:27:34.451
