just raise your hand.

00:27:34.451 --> 00:27:34.950
All right.

00:27:34.950 --> 00:27:36.533
So what we're going
to do is I'm going

00:27:36.533 --> 00:27:40.650
to ask you to just
keep those with you.

00:27:40.650 --> 00:27:42.630
We're going to do
another activity later

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:44.670
on using those as
a starting point,

00:27:44.670 --> 00:27:49.860
but I want you to just
keep that sorting with you.

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:52.800
Any comments or questions
about the experience,

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:53.860
about what you just did?

00:27:58.330 --> 00:28:00.820
Was it easy?

00:28:00.820 --> 00:28:02.980
No.

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:04.349
It can sometimes be a challenge.

00:28:04.349 --> 00:28:05.890
Well, what the heck
you were supposed

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:07.002
to do with this anyway?

00:28:07.002 --> 00:28:08.710
What do I really want
them to do with it?

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:12.460
This is the beginning
of that process whereby

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:15.640
you define exactly what it
is you want students to do,

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:17.532
know or be able to do.

00:28:17.532 --> 00:28:19.240
And then you can start
to think about how

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:22.360
you're going to assess whether
or not they can do it or not.

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:24.460
But it's very
different if I were

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:27.040
to say I want everybody
to be able to state

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:29.994
the first law of
thermodynamics versus I

00:28:29.994 --> 00:28:32.410
want you to be able to use the
first law of thermodynamics

00:28:32.410 --> 00:28:37.480
to define chemical, mechanical,
and thermal equilibrium

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:40.672
in a simple composite system.

00:28:40.672 --> 00:28:41.380
That's different.

00:28:41.380 --> 00:28:42.606
That's very different.

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:47.750
So that's what we're
starting to do.

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:53.440
So now we have
kind of the seeds.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:59.530
We thought about which topics
kind of we want to have,

00:28:59.530 --> 00:29:01.690
what we want to do with
each of the topics.

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:04.910
But now we really have to turn
them into learning outcomes,

00:29:04.910 --> 00:29:06.274
into real statements.

00:29:06.274 --> 00:29:07.690
By the end of this
class, you will

00:29:07.690 --> 00:29:13.600
be able to, by the end of this
course, you will be able to.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:17.980
And just as an aside,
remember that sometimes you'll

00:29:17.980 --> 00:29:20.620
notice that for every class,
every session we have,

00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:22.510
I have learning outcomes.

00:29:22.510 --> 00:29:24.940
But there's also overarching
learning outcomes

00:29:24.940 --> 00:29:26.400
for the course.

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:31.350
So I will use them
interchangeably,

00:29:31.350 --> 00:29:34.360
but they'll be at a
slightly different scale.

00:29:34.360 --> 00:29:39.160
The ones for the class are a
little bit more fine grained.

00:29:39.160 --> 00:29:41.710
As was mentioned in the reading,
and as Gordon mentioned,

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:46.660
they have to be specific,
measurable, and realistic.

00:29:46.660 --> 00:29:49.180
If they don't have
those properties

00:29:49.180 --> 00:29:52.420
they're not going to be
particularly useful, or as

00:29:52.420 --> 00:29:54.220
useful.

00:29:54.220 --> 00:29:55.550
All right.

00:29:55.550 --> 00:30:00.550
And we'll see some examples
of that in just a sec.

00:30:00.550 --> 00:30:02.800
So here's what they're not.

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:04.810
They're not topics.

00:30:04.810 --> 00:30:06.760
So you came with topics.

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:10.420
You will leave today
with learning outcomes.

00:30:10.420 --> 00:30:14.470
But topics are not
learning outcomes.

00:30:14.470 --> 00:30:18.430
The first law of thermodynamics
is not a learning outcome.

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:20.650
You need a verb with it.

00:30:20.650 --> 00:30:22.369
What do you want me
to do, what do you

00:30:22.369 --> 00:30:24.160
want your students to
do with the first law

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:25.980
of thermodynamics?

00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:28.090
What do you want them to
know about the first law

00:30:28.090 --> 00:30:30.410
of thermodynamics?

00:30:30.410 --> 00:30:32.980
So they're not topics.

00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:34.765
They're not things
that you will do.

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:40.900
It's easy to say, I could
have a list a mile long.

00:30:40.900 --> 00:30:47.950
I will talk about the first
law of thermodynamics.

00:30:47.950 --> 00:30:49.660
I can check that
off pretty easily.

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:50.734
I mean I just did.

00:30:50.734 --> 00:30:52.900
I just talked about the
first law of thermodynamics.

00:30:52.900 --> 00:30:56.410
It says nothing about what
you learned about it, what

00:30:56.410 --> 00:30:58.090
your students learned about it.

00:30:58.090 --> 00:31:00.430
So it's not about you.

00:31:00.430 --> 00:31:02.840
Get over it.

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:03.506
That was a joke.

00:31:06.447 --> 00:31:07.530
It's not value statements.

00:31:07.530 --> 00:31:11.490
As Adrian pointed out, some
of these think this is easy,

00:31:11.490 --> 00:31:16.640
this is good, this is useful.

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:19.135
Any of those things don't
belong in a learning outcome.

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:25.590
And it's not your hopes and
dreams for your students.

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:28.074
I mean, ultimately, it is.

00:31:28.074 --> 00:31:30.240
You hope that they will be
able to use the first law

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:32.340
of thermodynamics, da, da, da.

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:34.440
But it's really about
what they're doing,

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:36.240
about what they're going to do.

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:39.500
So, no.

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:40.610
Here's a little example.

00:31:43.140 --> 00:31:45.990
This is just from like an
earth and planetary course.

00:31:45.990 --> 00:31:49.700
Students will understand
plate tectonics.

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:50.640
How's that?

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:57.520
Is that OK for a
learning outcome?

00:31:57.520 --> 00:31:58.438
Why not?

00:31:58.438 --> 00:32:01.924
AUDIENCE: It's too broad.

00:32:01.924 --> 00:32:04.140
JANET RANKIN: It's
not very specific.

00:32:04.140 --> 00:32:07.435
What the heck about
plate tectonics?

00:32:07.435 --> 00:32:07.935
What else?

00:32:11.620 --> 00:32:13.580
AUDIENCE: Measurable.

00:32:13.580 --> 00:32:14.760
JANET RANKIN: Thank you.

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:16.890
OK, the measurable part.

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:23.310
This word understand,
strike it from your brains.

00:32:23.310 --> 00:32:25.150
It's a property that we love.

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:27.120
We love understand.

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:30.590
But you can't
flippin' measure it.

00:32:30.590 --> 00:32:32.840
You can't go in
there and measure it.

00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:35.180
You can measure lots
of things that tell you

00:32:35.180 --> 00:32:37.220
whether students
understand, but you

00:32:37.220 --> 00:32:39.500
can't measure understanding.

00:32:42.180 --> 00:32:44.307
And I think we'll see that
with some more examples.

00:32:44.307 --> 00:32:46.390
I don't think anybody is
earth and planetary here.

00:32:49.050 --> 00:32:50.664
So how about this one?

00:32:50.664 --> 00:32:52.080
Students will be
able to interpret

00:32:52.080 --> 00:32:54.240
unfamiliar tectonic
settings based

00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:59.830
on information on volcanic
activity and seismicity.

00:32:59.830 --> 00:33:02.340
Again, I don't think any
of us are geologists.

00:33:02.340 --> 00:33:04.980
But the idea that I've
told, or the person

00:33:04.980 --> 00:33:08.310
has told us what
we're going to use

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:12.060
to interpret these
situations, and then we're

00:33:12.060 --> 00:33:15.417
going to make predictions based
on those interpretations, I

00:33:15.417 --> 00:33:17.610
mean, that's an assumption.

00:33:17.610 --> 00:33:21.426
So it's specific and
now it's measurable.

00:33:21.426 --> 00:33:22.800
Even though we're
not geologists,

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:24.750
I suspect we can
think of how we could

00:33:24.750 --> 00:33:29.220
write a test question that
would ask students to do this.

00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:32.910
And then we could see
whether they did it or not.

00:33:32.910 --> 00:33:35.370
So that's measurable.

00:33:35.370 --> 00:33:40.715
And probably, by doing this,
by having students do this,

00:33:40.715 --> 00:33:42.840
we get a pretty good
measurement about whether they

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:46.900
understand plate tectonics.

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:50.877
But it's much more specific
and it's much more measurable.

00:33:58.944 --> 00:34:01.110
From here, this is from the
University of Minnesota,

00:34:01.110 --> 00:34:03.590
