00:55:29.856 --> 00:55:32.760
JANET RANKIN: It's
instructor centered.

00:55:32.760 --> 00:55:33.376
What else?

00:55:33.376 --> 00:55:36.372
AUDIENCE: But it's measurable.

00:55:36.372 --> 00:55:38.580
JANET RANKIN: Well, I can
measure that I provided it.

00:55:38.580 --> 00:55:41.690
Here, I provided
these handouts, right?

00:55:41.690 --> 00:55:42.390
OK.

00:55:42.390 --> 00:55:43.590
Check.

00:55:43.590 --> 00:55:44.990
It happened.

00:55:44.990 --> 00:55:47.040
Whether or not you could
do anything with them,

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:50.199
I don't know at
this point, right?

00:55:50.199 --> 00:55:50.990
That's the problem.

00:55:50.990 --> 00:55:53.833
AUDIENCE: It doesn't tell
us what kind of problem

00:55:53.833 --> 00:55:55.920
and what kind of tools
we're going to use.

00:55:55.920 --> 00:55:57.795
Just who gets to
choose the strategies.

00:55:57.795 --> 00:55:59.290
JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:55:59.290 --> 00:55:59.790
Right.

00:55:59.790 --> 00:56:02.520
It's very, very general,
totally not specific.

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:04.230
So what could we do?

00:56:04.230 --> 00:56:06.750
I mean, we don't know what
this instructor had in mind,

00:56:06.750 --> 00:56:08.700
but what could you do
if this was your class?

00:56:08.700 --> 00:56:09.491
What would you say?

00:56:09.491 --> 00:56:11.685
AUDIENCE: What about
develop instead of provide?

00:56:11.685 --> 00:56:13.890
JANET RANKIN: Develop.

00:56:13.890 --> 00:56:15.930
And again, it would have
to be student centered,

00:56:15.930 --> 00:56:19.470
so the student will be
able to develop problem

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:21.540
solving tools and strategies.

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:24.900
That's for x, exactly.

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:28.620
We want to make it a little
more specific and a little more

00:56:28.620 --> 00:56:32.580
focused, because
that's pretty broad.

00:56:32.580 --> 00:56:34.219
I mean, I have
developed a problem

00:56:34.219 --> 00:56:35.760
solving strategy
that lets me get out

00:56:35.760 --> 00:56:38.190
the door without tripping.

00:56:38.190 --> 00:56:41.340
Does that mean I satisfied
your learning outcomes?

00:56:41.340 --> 00:56:44.070
Probably not.

00:56:44.070 --> 00:56:48.570
So in order to do something--

00:56:48.570 --> 00:56:51.000
Use thermodynamics to
solve engineering problems.

00:56:56.536 --> 00:56:58.675
AUDIENCE: That's not
specific as well.

00:56:58.675 --> 00:57:00.725
JANET RANKIN: It's
not specific at all.

00:57:00.725 --> 00:57:04.209
AUDIENCE: Engineering
is [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:04.209 --> 00:57:05.000
JANET RANKIN: Yeah.

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:08.240
I mean, it's crazy broad on
a number of fronts, right?

00:57:08.240 --> 00:57:10.280
I mean, it's like
engineering is huge.

00:57:10.280 --> 00:57:12.680
Thermodynamics is
pretty darn big, too.

00:57:12.680 --> 00:57:18.240
So which part of thermodynamics,
which part of engineering?

00:57:21.750 --> 00:57:23.503
Build an SAE race car.

00:57:23.503 --> 00:57:24.489
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:24.489 --> 00:57:25.475
JANET RANKIN: What?

00:57:28.433 --> 00:57:29.907
AUDIENCE: It's not realistic.

00:57:29.907 --> 00:57:30.740
JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:57:30.740 --> 00:57:32.660
It's pretty specific.

00:57:32.660 --> 00:57:34.910
Build a functioning
SAE race car.

00:57:34.910 --> 00:57:38.000
It's very specific,
and I can totally

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.292
think of the metric
of how I would measure

00:57:40.292 --> 00:57:41.500
whether students could do it.

00:57:41.500 --> 00:57:43.730
I would just ask them
to build the race car.

00:57:43.730 --> 00:57:45.860
But they're never going
to do it in a class,

00:57:45.860 --> 00:57:48.230
in one class period,
in one course.

00:57:48.230 --> 00:57:51.920
It's unrealistic, exactly.

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:54.200
Learn to use Laplace
transforms to solve

00:57:54.200 --> 00:57:56.234
differential equations.

00:57:56.234 --> 00:57:59.433
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:59.433 --> 00:58:02.010
JANET RANKIN: It's funny.

00:58:02.010 --> 00:58:04.900
I mean, you can
imagine the instructor

00:58:04.900 --> 00:58:07.530
saying you will
learn to use that.

00:58:07.530 --> 00:58:13.580
But let's go, Katherine, work
your magic with this one.

00:58:16.564 --> 00:58:23.452
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:23.452 --> 00:58:24.475
JANET RANKIN: Right.

00:58:24.475 --> 00:58:26.600
You're my go-to person for
when you want to get rid

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:27.869
of all the extra words.

00:58:27.869 --> 00:58:28.910
I'm going to call on you.

00:58:28.910 --> 00:58:29.410
Right.

00:58:29.410 --> 00:58:31.995
Use Laplace transforms.

00:58:31.995 --> 00:58:32.870
That you can measure.

00:58:32.870 --> 00:58:34.760
You can give them
an equation and see

00:58:34.760 --> 00:58:38.459
if they can use Laplace
transforms to solve it.

00:58:38.459 --> 00:58:40.250
And yes, you might want
to be a little more

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:42.541
specific about the kinds of
differential equations they

00:58:42.541 --> 00:58:48.415
use, and know how to upper
diagonalize a matrix.

00:58:51.090 --> 00:58:52.207
Katherine.

00:58:52.207 --> 00:58:52.706
AUDIENCE: .

00:58:52.706 --> 00:58:55.600
Upper diagonalize a matrix.

00:58:55.600 --> 00:58:58.300
JANET RANKIN: Upper
diagonalize a matrix.

00:58:58.300 --> 00:58:59.770
That's all you
have to say, right?

00:58:59.770 --> 00:59:02.620
Forget the extra words.

00:59:02.620 --> 00:59:06.610
And that is really, I have just
written the assessment question

00:59:06.610 --> 00:59:07.510
for that.

00:59:07.510 --> 00:59:10.060
I know it's totally measurable.

00:59:10.060 --> 00:59:13.780
I give you a matrix and I ask
you to upper diagonalize it.

00:59:13.780 --> 00:59:16.330
I haven't given it away.

00:59:16.330 --> 00:59:19.860
I haven't told you you will
upper diagonalize this matrix,

00:59:19.860 --> 00:59:20.560
right?

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:22.450
Memorize these
equations that you're

00:59:22.450 --> 00:59:25.480
going to need to write down in
order to upper diagonalize it.

00:59:25.480 --> 00:59:29.440
But I have told you that
that's what's expected of you.

00:59:29.440 --> 00:59:31.238
AUDIENCE: I have
a comment on it.

00:59:31.238 --> 00:59:33.733
It's pretty useful
when a student

00:59:33.733 --> 00:59:36.730
is trying to evaluate
the use of the class.

00:59:36.730 --> 00:59:41.226
For example, the career
fair tomorrow [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:41.226 --> 00:59:43.218
There's a million
[INAUDIBLE] to get jobs.

00:59:43.218 --> 00:59:45.210
OK, how are they
going to evaluate me?

00:59:45.210 --> 00:59:46.635
And if you could
come in and say,

00:59:46.635 --> 00:59:48.297
this happened and
this is what we

00:59:48.297 --> 00:59:51.560
did, as opposed to
having, or have them

00:59:51.560 --> 00:59:53.269
evaluate me on some
random knowledge.

00:59:53.269 --> 00:59:55.060
And then I don't know
that I could respond,

00:59:55.060 --> 00:59:58.880
but I do know stuff.

00:59:58.880 --> 01:00:02.526
So this is really helpful
in kind of a broader sense.

01:00:02.526 --> 01:00:03.801
JANET RANKIN: Right.

01:00:03.801 --> 01:00:04.300
Great.

01:00:04.300 --> 01:00:04.900
No, I'm glad.

01:00:04.900 --> 01:00:06.530
And I think it's so true.

01:00:06.530 --> 01:00:09.880
And people often think,
well, you're giving it away.

01:00:09.880 --> 01:00:11.710
But you're not
giving anything away.

01:00:11.710 --> 01:00:14.020
You're just telling
them the expectations.

01:00:14.020 --> 01:00:15.880
You're not giving
them the problems,

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:20.350
you're not teaching to the test,
but you're just telling them

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:26.290
what they're going to be able
to do at the kind of high level,

01:00:26.290 --> 01:00:28.816
or medium level.

01:00:28.816 --> 01:00:30.940
You're telling what they're
going to be able to do.

01:00:30.940 --> 01:00:33.310
I will say-- so ABET,
the Accreditation Board

01:00:33.310 --> 01:00:35.050
for Engineering Teaching--

01:00:35.050 --> 01:00:38.170
every accredited engineering
program has to list,

01:00:38.170 --> 01:00:40.352
they have A through K outcomes.

01:00:40.352 --> 01:00:41.560
And if you look it up, ABET--

01:00:44.230 --> 01:00:48.010
and I'm sure you see
us as accredited--

01:00:48.010 --> 01:00:54.870
if you look up,
they have to, they

01:00:54.870 --> 01:00:57.060
used to do a lot
more bean counting.

01:00:57.060 --> 01:00:59.100
But what they would
do is the outcomes

01:00:59.100 --> 01:01:04.340
would be critical thinking
and problem solving skills,

01:01:04.340 --> 01:01:06.420
and they were a
little bit broad.

01:01:06.420 --> 01:01:08.910
But every department
that got accredited

01:01:08.910 --> 01:01:14.130
had to show how various courses
contributed to the outcomes.

01:01:14.130 --> 01:01:19.350
So somewhere in your department
should be a pretty detailed

01:01:19.350 --> 01:01:22.770
list of how 6 double
00 whatever, did this.

01:01:22.770 --> 01:01:23.980
Or 6 yada, yada--

01:01:23.980 --> 01:01:25.705
I know your grad
students-- but did this.

01:01:25.705 --> 01:01:27.330
The problem is they
don't have to do it

01:01:27.330 --> 01:01:28.440
for grad student courses.

01:01:28.440 --> 01:01:32.430
But it might be helpful if you
looked at that, because I would

01:01:32.430 --> 01:01:34.770
imagine that sometimes
the recruiters would

01:01:34.770 --> 01:01:38.550
be looking at that information,
so that might be a commonality.

01:01:38.550 --> 01:01:42.240
But every program in the US
that's accredited has to have,

01:01:42.240 --> 01:01:46.270
show at least how they've
addressed those outcomes.

01:01:46.270 --> 01:01:48.441
So you might want to
take a look at that.

01:01:48.441 --> 01:01:50.190
But yeah, if it was a
little more explicit

01:01:50.190 --> 01:01:51.437
it would certainly be better.

01:01:51.437 --> 01:01:52.520
And I'm glad it's helpful.

01:01:55.290 --> 01:01:57.240
So I think we can
see, you can start

01:01:57.240 --> 01:02:00.150
to see how there are better
and worse learning outcomes,

01:02:00.150 --> 01:02:03.840
that if they're not measurable
they're not so useful.

01:02:03.840 --> 01:02:06.580
If they are measurable,
they're quite useful.

01:02:06.580 --> 01:02:12.620
So now what I'd like to do
is revisit the worksheet.

01:02:12.620 --> 01:02:16.470
And what we can
do is we're going

01:02:16.470 --> 01:02:20.490
to take about five minutes
where you just sit quietly

01:02:20.490 --> 01:02:25.720
and write out specific
intended learning outcomes.

01:02:25.720 --> 01:02:29.160
So you'll be able to upper
diagonalize a matrix,

01:02:29.160 --> 01:02:33.180
you will be able to
use Laplace transforms

01:02:33.180 --> 01:02:35.790
to solve this type of
differential equation,

01:02:35.790 --> 01:02:39.450
whatever you've
written in this column.

01:02:39.450 --> 01:02:41.460
And note that if you
put it in this column,

01:02:41.460 --> 01:02:43.470
let's say you put it
in the apply column,

01:02:43.470 --> 01:02:46.110
then when you write the learning
outcome it's going to be you

01:02:46.110 --> 01:02:51.870
will be able to interpret
data using blah, blah, blah.

01:02:51.870 --> 01:03:01.380
You will be able to model
the vibration, model a car

01:03:01.380 --> 01:03:04.770
suspension system using
linearization techniques.

01:03:04.770 --> 01:03:08.280
They're going to be whatever,
wherever you put it in the box.

01:03:08.280 --> 01:03:09.750
These are some of
the verbs, these

01:03:09.750 --> 01:03:13.295
are the verbs you're going to
use in your learning outcome.

01:03:13.295 --> 01:03:14.170
Does that make sense?

01:03:17.050 --> 01:03:20.740
And I have even more verbs
for you if that's helpful.

01:03:20.740 --> 01:03:22.401
Did I pass those out?

01:03:22.401 --> 01:03:23.275
You got those, right?

01:03:23.275 --> 01:03:23.980
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:03:23.980 --> 01:03:25.480
JANET RANKIN: So
there's more verbs.

01:03:25.480 --> 01:03:26.950
It's the same thing.

01:03:26.950 --> 01:03:28.960
I mean, it's consistent.

01:03:28.960 --> 01:03:31.000
So take five minutes by
yourself and do that.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:33.220
And then you're going
to get into pairs

01:03:33.220 --> 01:03:35.380
and you're going to discuss.

01:03:35.380 --> 01:03:38.320
You're going to trade worksheets
and give each other feedback.

01:03:38.320 --> 01:03:38.980
All right?

01:03:38.980 --> 01:03:44.310
So five minutes of quiet
and then we'll pair up.

01:04:03.540 --> 01:04:06.655
So if you can pair up,
you don't necessarily

01:04:06.655 --> 01:04:09.030
have to pair up with people
that are sitting next to you.

01:04:09.030 --> 01:04:12.060
You might want to get a
different perspective,

01:04:12.060 --> 01:04:13.785
so feel free to get
up and move around.

01:04:13.785 --> 01:04:16.780
You can talk to somebody
that wasn't in your group.

01:04:16.780 --> 01:04:19.330
So maybe if you go back
and talk with Alex, maybe.

01:04:19.330 --> 01:04:20.890
We need one group of three.

01:04:20.890 --> 01:04:22.810
Oh, are you a group of three?

01:04:22.810 --> 01:04:28.740
So now just trade sheets
of paper with your partner,

01:04:28.740 --> 01:04:33.670
or if you're a threesome you
can figure out how to do it.

01:04:33.670 --> 01:04:38.010
And then review the learning
outcomes critically.

01:04:38.010 --> 01:04:40.710
Guys, just one sec.

01:04:40.710 --> 01:04:43.530
So just review your partner's
learning outcomes critically.

01:04:43.530 --> 01:04:45.570
Make sure that they're
measurable, realistic,

01:04:45.570 --> 01:04:46.650
and specific.

01:04:46.650 --> 01:04:48.210
If your partner
has used the word

01:04:48.210 --> 01:04:50.910
understand, help him or
her work through that

01:04:50.910 --> 01:04:53.340
to get a better word.

01:04:53.340 --> 01:04:56.820
So you're going to be
a critical friend here.

01:04:56.820 --> 01:04:59.730
And then you guys can
discuss how to improve it.

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:02.640
And then I'm going to pass
around some flip chart paper

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:05.880
and each one of you
will write, maybe

01:05:05.880 --> 01:05:08.310
just write your name at the
top, and write two or three

01:05:08.310 --> 01:05:10.534
learning outcomes on
the flip chart paper.

01:05:10.534 --> 01:05:12.450
And then we can stick
them up around the room,

01:05:12.450 --> 01:05:14.580
and then everybody can
see everybody else's,

01:05:14.580 --> 01:05:16.652
all learning outcomes.

01:05:16.652 --> 01:05:21.170
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:05:22.587 --> 01:05:24.045
JANET RANKIN: Was
there a question?

01:05:24.045 --> 01:05:24.753
AUDIENCE: Oh, no.

01:05:24.753 --> 01:05:25.600
I just think--

01:05:25.600 --> 01:05:27.320
AUDIENCE: I think [INAUDIBLE].

01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:35.340
JANET RANKIN: How
are you guys doing?

01:05:35.340 --> 01:05:37.950
Doing OK?

01:05:37.950 --> 01:05:41.868
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:05:58.286 --> 01:06:01.470
JANET RANKIN: So you can use
this zone if you need it.

01:06:05.490 --> 01:06:08.160
As you're looking
at other people's

01:06:08.160 --> 01:06:11.910
learning outcomes,
think about how clear,

01:06:11.910 --> 01:06:14.130
how easy it would
be, or not easy,

01:06:14.130 --> 01:06:17.130
to come up with an exam
question, or a project,

01:06:17.130 --> 01:06:20.070
or an assessment or
measurement of whether

01:06:20.070 --> 01:06:23.580
or not the student reached,
attained the learning outcome.

01:06:23.580 --> 01:06:25.630
You can put them up
here, Ina and Shau.

01:06:34.841 --> 01:06:35.340
OK.

01:06:35.340 --> 01:06:37.810
And as I said, make sure that
you've read everybody else's.

01:06:37.810 --> 01:06:40.750
I'm going to say a
few words about them.

01:06:45.550 --> 01:06:47.500
I think we may have a record.

01:06:47.500 --> 01:06:51.400
This is like the first
time ever that no one

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:54.850
has used the word
understand, which I think

01:06:54.850 --> 01:06:56.370
you're all to be commended for.

01:07:00.190 --> 01:07:04.900
So David, make sure you
don't write understand.

01:07:04.900 --> 01:07:06.736
You build me up just
to knock me down.

01:07:12.110 --> 01:07:13.597
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:13.597 --> 01:07:15.430
JANET RANKIN: You can,
or you don't have to.

01:07:15.430 --> 01:07:16.179
It doesn't matter.

01:07:18.680 --> 01:07:24.260
Does anyone have any comments,
either about the exercise

01:07:24.260 --> 01:07:29.510
itself, or about somebody's
learning outcomes,

01:07:29.510 --> 01:07:30.380
that you see around?

01:07:33.250 --> 01:07:35.260
Again, the
measurement, the thing

01:07:35.260 --> 01:07:37.510
you want to look at when you
look at your own learning

01:07:37.510 --> 01:07:40.640
outcomes and those of others, is
are they specific, measurable,

01:07:40.640 --> 01:07:42.940
and realistic?

01:07:42.940 --> 01:07:46.540
And would you know
if a student achieved

01:07:46.540 --> 01:07:48.500
those learning outcomes?

01:07:48.500 --> 01:07:53.740
So I would say about 90%
of these are very specific,

01:07:53.740 --> 01:07:54.980
which is great.

01:07:54.980 --> 01:07:59.470
I mean, there's some
incredibly specific ones here.

01:07:59.470 --> 01:08:04.060
The more specific, the
easier it is to measure.

01:08:04.060 --> 01:08:04.900
So that's one thing.

01:08:04.900 --> 01:08:06.610
That's a useful thing.

01:08:06.610 --> 01:08:08.950
You want to make sure
you don't get so specific

01:08:08.950 --> 01:08:11.980
that there's only like one
question you could ask.

01:08:11.980 --> 01:08:14.170
So that's the balance.

01:08:14.170 --> 01:08:16.270
Sometimes you can't
tell that unless you're

01:08:16.270 --> 01:08:18.355
in the discipline.

01:08:18.355 --> 01:08:24.040
Do we have other comments about
any of these learning outcomes,

01:08:24.040 --> 01:08:29.279
something you don't
get, something that

01:08:29.279 --> 01:08:30.784
looks particularly interesting?

01:08:33.990 --> 01:08:34.890
Yes, Gordon.

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:38.355
Perhaps you can sit down
if you're done reading.

01:08:38.355 --> 01:08:42.323
AUDIENCE: I'm looking around
and I'm seeing [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:52.739 --> 01:08:54.723
I don't know how
it's going to be.

01:08:54.723 --> 01:08:56.211
How are we going to test that?

01:08:56.211 --> 01:09:00.740
JANET RANKIN: Well, I guess you
have to come up with a reaction

01:09:00.740 --> 01:09:03.810
that you're confident
they haven't seen before.

01:09:03.810 --> 01:09:08.359
So if you can do that, then
you can ask them to propose

01:09:08.359 --> 01:09:11.560
a mechanism for it, I suppose.

01:09:11.560 --> 01:09:13.370
If the person that
wrote it wants to--

01:09:13.370 --> 01:09:15.578
I know who wrote it-- but
if the person that wrote it

01:09:15.578 --> 01:09:18.600
wants to talk a little bit
about it, that would be great.

01:09:18.600 --> 01:09:19.100
If not--

01:09:19.100 --> 01:09:22.390
AUDIENCE: OK, So a
lot of people are

01:09:22.390 --> 01:09:26.150
